          "title": "The pivot: 'Yet God is my King' (74:12)",
          "body": "Everything in the psalm turns on one word in verse 12: 'Yet' (*we* in Hebrew, an adversative conjunction carrying enormous theological weight). After eleven verses of mounting evidence for divine abandonment, a single confessional statement arrests the descent: 'Yet God is my King from of old, who works deeds of deliverance in the midst of the earth.' The syntax shifts from 'Why?' and 'How long?' to 'You' — the second-person declarations that fill verses 13–17. And the personal pronoun shifts from 'we/us' (the community's plural grief) to 'my King' — a moment of personal covenant faith embedded in communal lament. This is the psalm's pastoral heart. Asaph does not resolve the tension between the burned sanctuary and God's lordship; he holds both simultaneously. As Spurgeon observed, faith does not wait for the smoke to clear before confessing the King. The 'Yet' of verse 12 is the grammar of biblical hope: not optimism that denies present darkness, but confession that refuses to let present darkness have the final word."
