          "title": "The psalm's canonical and theological function",
          "body": "Psalm 74 performs a necessary canonical function: it gives the community of faith a model for praying when God appears absent and the evidence for His presence has been destroyed. The psalm does not resolve theologically into a tidy theodicy; it ends with unanswered imperatives and an unquenched fire. This incompleteness is deliberate. In the canonical context of Book III (Psalms 73–89), Psalm 73 provided the individual's hard-won resolution through nearness to the sanctuary; Psalm 74 provides the community's unresolved lament when the sanctuary is gone. Together they demonstrate that faith's posture ranges from settled confidence to raw petition — and both are legitimate before God. The New Testament does not eliminate the psalm but deepens it: the sanctuary that was finally and permanently desecrated was the body of Jesus Christ (John 2:19), whose destruction was also the means of the covenant's ultimate fulfillment (Hebrews 9:15). The 'turtledove' given over to the beast (74:19) finds its antitype in the Lamb slain before the foundation of the world (Revelation 13:8). The creation-King who crushed Leviathan (74:14) is the one before whom the dragon is finally thrown down (Revelation 20:2). The psalm's unanswered 'How long?' (74:10) is taken up in Revelation 6:10 and answered only at the last day."
