        "body": "Verse 12 is the hinge of the entire psalm, and it deserves separate treatment as an interpretive movement. The adversative 'Yet' (*we*- in Hebrew — a simple conjunction that carries enormous rhetorical weight here) marks the pivot from lament to confession. Everything in verses 1–11 has been oriented by 'Why?' and 'How long?'; verse 12 reorients by 'Yet.' This is not a resolution of the problem — the temple is still in ruins, the prophets are still silent, the enemy is still roaring. The 'Yet' does not deny any of that. It adds a confession that holds the opposite truth simultaneously.\n\nThe personal pronoun is significant: 'God is *my* King.' In eleven verses of corporate lament, this is the first singular first-person statement. Asaph momentarily steps out of the communal 'we' to make an individual confession of covenant loyalty. This is not spiritual individualism; it is the move that enables the community's petition to continue. When corporate experience has produced only questions, individual faith can still confess what communal circumstances have obscured. Tim Keller (*The Songs of Jesus*, 2015) notes that this structure — lament moving through confession into petition — is the biblical pattern for holding suffering and faith together without collapsing either.\n\nThe content of the confession is specifically historical: 'from of old' (*qedem*), the same word used in verse 2 for the antiquity of the covenant purchase. God has been King before the present crisis began, which means the crisis does not define His reign. And the present-participle 'works deeds of deliverance' (*poel yeshuot*) carries iterative force — this is what God characteristically does. The word *yeshuah* (salvation/deliverance) is the root of the name Joshua and of Jesus (*Yeshua*). Asaph is confessing that the God he is petitioning is by nature and history a saving King — and he is about to spend six verses proving it from creation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Melekh* (king, 74:12) — the royal title applied to God as cosmic sovereign, closely associated in the Psalter with enthronement theology (Psalms 93, 95–99). *Yeshuah* (salvation, 74:12) — acts of rescue, victories won on behalf of the helpless. The combination *melekh...poel yeshuot* ('king...working salvations') in a single verse captures the whole argument: the One who reigns is the One who rescues."
