        "excerpt": "Consider the covenant; for the dark places of the land are full of the habitations of violence. Arise, O God, and plead Your own cause.",
        "body": "The psalm's final movement (74:18–23) is structured around five imperatives addressed to God: 'Remember' (74:18), 'Do not deliver' (74:19), 'Do not forget' (74:19), 'Consider the covenant' (74:20), 'Arise' (74:22). Each imperative is grounded in a specific aspect of God's covenant identity, and together they build from evidence to argument to demand.\n\nThe grounding of petition in the enemy's theological offense (74:18) is a sophisticated rhetorical move. Asaph does not primarily appeal to the congregation's suffering — he appeals to God's name. 'The enemy has reviled, and a foolish people has spurned Your name' (74:18). The fool (*naval*) of verse 18 echoes Psalm 14:1 — the one who in his heart dismisses God as inactive or absent. The Babylonians are not merely political conquerors; they are theological provocateurs. Their victory implies the impotence of YHWH. This framing shifts the argument from 'God, please help us because we are suffering' to 'God, act because Your own reputation is at stake.' Jonathan Edwards (*Miscellanies*, No. 1208) argued that prayer which appeals to God's glory is the most powerful form of petition, because it aligns the petitioner's request with God's own ultimate purpose — to display His own name.\n\nThe appeal to 'consider the covenant' (74:20) is the psalm's theological climax. *Navat berit* — 'look attentively at the covenant' — is a legal term: to examine a document, to assess obligations. Asaph is asking God to look at what He has sworn. The evidence that the covenant promises remain unfulfilled is immediately given: 'the dark places of the land are full of the habitations of violence' (74:20). The covenant promised the land as a dwelling of righteousness; it is now a dwelling of *chamas* (violence) and *machshakh* (darkness) — the precise opposite of what God swore. The psalmist's argument is that the covenant itself is indicted by the current state of affairs.\n\nThe final petition — 'Arise, O God, and plead Your own cause' (74:22) — uses the legal term *riv*, meaning a lawsuit or legal dispute. The psalmist is asking God to take up His own legal case, to act as prosecuting attorney against the fools who have reviled His name. This is a remarkable inversion: the community has been presenting God with evidence and arguments throughout the psalm, but at the end they give the case back to Him. The final verse (74:23) grounds the urgency: the enemy's uproar 'ascends continually' — unceasing blasphemy is reaching God's ears even now, and He is asked not to forget it. The psalm ends without a reported answer, without a resolution, but also without despair. It ends with the community having done what covenant people do in catastrophe: presented their case fully, confessed their King honestly, and left the outcome with the God who is faithful to His own name.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Riv* (cause/lawsuit, 74:22) — a legal dispute or contention, the same word used in Micah 6:2 ('the LORD has a case against His people') and in Jeremiah 25:31 ('the LORD has a controversy with the nations'). *Berit* (covenant, 74:20) — the binding suzerainty treaty between YHWH and Israel; to ask God to 'consider' it is to invoke the treaty's stipulations and the divine patron's obligations. *Naval* (fool, 74:18, 22) — not intellectual foolishness but moral-theological rejection of God's rule; the word used in Psalm 14:1, Deuteronomy 32:6, and 2 Samuel 13:13 for the most contemptible form of wickedness."
